<doc id="55610" wikidata="Q862761" url="?curid=55610" title="Interior (topology)">
<text>In mathematics, specifically in topology,
the interior of a subset of a topological space is the union of all subsets of that are open in .
A point that is in the interior of is an interior point of .

The interior of is the complement of the closure of the complement of .
In this sense interior and closure are dual notions.

The exterior of a set is the complement of the closure of ; it consists of the points that are in neither the set nor its boundary.
The interior, boundary, and exterior of a subset together partition the whole space into three blocks (or fewer when one or more of these is empty).

The interior and exterior of a closed curve are a slightly different concept; see the Jordan curve theorem.

==Definitions==

===Interior point===

If formula_1 is a subset of a Euclidean space, then formula_2 is an interior point of formula_1 if there exists an open ball centered at formula_2 which is completely contained in formula_5
(This is illustrated in the introductory section to this article.)

This definition generalizes to any subset formula_1 of a metric space formula_7 with metric formula_8: formula_2 is an interior point of formula_1 if there exists a real number formula_11 such that formula_12 is in formula_1 whenever the distance formula_14

This definition generalizes to topological spaces by replacing &quot;open ball&quot; with &quot;open set&quot;.
If formula_1 is a subset of a topological space formula_7 then formula_2 is an of formula_1 in formula_7 if formula_2 is contained in an open subset of formula_7 that is completely contained in formula_5
(Equivalently, formula_2 is an interior point of formula_1 if formula_1 is a neighbourhood of formula_26)

===Interior of a set===

The interior of a subset formula_1 of a topological space formula_28 denoted by formula_29 or formula_30 or formula_31 can be defined in any of the following equivalent ways:
# formula_30 is the largest open subset of formula_7 contained in formula_5
# formula_30 is the union of all open sets of formula_7 contained in formula_5
# formula_30 is the set of all interior points of formula_5
If the space formula_7 is understood from context then the shorter notation formula_30 is usually preferred to formula_42

==Examples==
*In any space, the interior of the empty set is the empty set.
*In any space formula_28 if formula_44 then formula_45
*If formula_7 is the real line formula_47 (with the standard topology), then formula_48 whereas the interior of the set formula_49 of rational numbers is empty: formula_50
*If formula_7 is the complex plane formula_52 then formula_53
*In any Euclidean space, the interior of any finite set is the empty set.

On the set of real numbers, one can put other topologies rather than the standard one:

*If formula_7 is the real numbers formula_47 with the lower limit topology, then formula_56
*If one considers on formula_47 the topology in which every set is open, then formula_58
*If one considers on formula_47 the topology in which the only open sets are the empty set and formula_47 itself, then formula_61 is the empty set.

These examples show that the interior of a set depends upon the topology of the underlying space.
The last two examples are special cases of the following.

*In any discrete space, since every set is open, every set is equal to its interior.
*In any indiscrete space formula_28 since the only open sets are the empty set and formula_7 itself, formula_64 and for every proper subset formula_1 of formula_28 formula_30 is the empty set.

