where formula_7 is the topological space containing formula_107 and the backslash formula_108 denotes set-theoretic difference.
Therefore, the abstract theory of closure operators and the Kuratowski closure axioms can be readily translated into the language of interior operators, by replacing sets with their complements in formula_71

In general, the interior operator does not commute with unions. However, in a complete metric space the following result does hold:

The result above implies that every complete metric space is a Baire space.

==Exterior of a set==

The exterior of a subset formula_1 of a topological space formula_28 denoted by formula_112 or simply formula_113 is the largest open set disjoint from formula_107 namely, it is the union of all open sets in formula_7 that are disjoint from formula_5 The exterior is the interior of the complement, which is the same as the complement of the closure; in formulas,
formula_117

Similarly, the interior is the exterior of the complement:
formula_118

The interior, boundary, and exterior of a set formula_1 together partition the whole space into three blocks (or fewer when one or more of these is empty):
formula_120
where formula_121 denotes the boundary of formula_5 The interior and exterior are always open, while the boundary is closed.

Some of the properties of the exterior operator are unlike those of the interior operator:
* The exterior operator reverses inclusions; if formula_123 then formula_124
* The exterior operator is not idempotent. It does have the property that formula_125

==Interior-disjoint shapes==

Two shapes formula_126 and formula_127 are called &quot;interior-disjoint&quot; if the intersection of their interiors is empty.
Interior-disjoint shapes may or may not intersect in their boundary.

